:::summary
*The Lord of the Rings* (1954–55) is J.R.R. Tolkien's monumental fantasy epic — widely regarded as the greatest work of the genre and one of the most influential novels of the twentieth century. Following humble hobbit Frodo Baggins on a quest to destroy the One Ring of Power in the fires of Mount Doom, it is at heart a story about courage, friendship, self-sacrifice, the corruption of power, and the grace that enables ordinary people to do extraordinary things. Tolkien, a devout Catholic, wove profound Christian themes of redemption, providence, and mercy throughout its pages.
:::

